goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rates across all states?

goals.visualization: line chart of unemployment rates by month
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there are any seasonal trends in unemployment rates and if certain months have higher or lower rates than others.

goals.question: Is there a correlation between unemployment rates and state population?

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='date', y='rate', data=data, ci=None)
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rates over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Unemployment Rate', loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='state', y='rate', data=data, ci=None, palette='viridis')
    plt.title('Which state has the highest and lowest unemployment rates?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    max_rate = data['rate'].max()
    min_rate = data['rate'].min()
    plt.axhline(max_rate, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Max Rate: {max_rate:.2f}')
    plt.axhline(min_rate, color='g', linestyle='--', label=f'Min Rate: {min_rate:.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='rate', bins=30, kde=True, color='blue', alpha=0.5)
    plt.axvline(data['rate'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['rate'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment rates across all states?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data['month'] = data['date'].dt.month

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='month', y='rate', data=data, ci=None)
    plt.title('How does the unemployment rate vary by season?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(range(1, 13), ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='state', y='rate', hue='state', palette='tab20', legend='full')
    plt.title('Is there a correlation between unemployment rates and state population?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='State', loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.15, 1))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
